==Finnish==
===Etymology===
{{prefix|fi|yhteis|gloss1=joint, shared|koulu|gloss2=school}}
===Pronunciation===
{{fi-p|yhteis-koulu}}
===Noun===
{{fi-noun}}
# {{lb|fi|dated}} [[co-ed]] [[school]] {{gloss|school that teaches both girls and boys}}.
====Usage notes====
Currently all schools are co-ed in Finland and this term is therefore almost fallen out of use, except for the names of schools. For current school terminology, see {{m|fi|esikoulu}}, {{m|fi|peruskoulu}} and {{m|fi|lukio}}. In its time, '''''yhteiskoulu''''' referred either to a {{m|fi|keskikoulu||junior high school, grades 5 to 9}} or {{m|fi|oppikoulu||grammar school, grades 5 to 12}} which taught both girls and boys. Co-eds for grades 10 to 12 were called {{m|fi|yhteislukio}}. The schools above grade 5 teaching only boys were formerly called {{m|fi|lyseo}} and those teaching only girls were called {{m|fi|tyttölyseo}}. Grades 1 to 4 ({{m|fi|kansakoulu}}) became obligatory for both sexes in 1921.
